220. oum . . . vellet: at a time when he wished; cf. 1, 1 : cum arbitrarer. — fervorne mentis: i.e. with that strict attention to definition characteristic of thc Stoice. We might expect animi for mentis; but mens is also used to denote the emotional nature—puniendi doloris: os avenqinq a hura—motus . . . miscere atque agitare: to rouse the passions and set them in serment—partim . . . partim: i.e. the Stoice, the Peripatetics; cf.
